##  The short: 


Structs: are a fundamental concept in programming that originated with the C programming language in the 1970s. Before structs, programmers had to manage each piece of data individually, which made it difficult to represent complex entities or real-world objects in code. Structs were introduced as a way to group related variables together under a single name, allowing a programmer to model objects with multiple attributes efficiently. Each variable inside a struct is called a field, and these fields can have different data types, such as integers, strings, or even other structs. This concept made it easier to organize, maintain, and scale programs, especially for large projects where multiple attributes of an object need to be handled together. Over time, structs became the foundation for more advanced data modeling and influenced object-oriented programming, where similar ideas are used to define classes and objects. Today, languages like Go, C, C++, and Rust use structs extensively, allowing developers to represent complex data in a clean and structured way while keeping code readable and modular.



